 
<!-- PJG STAG 4703 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 308(d) of the IFA, codified at 16 U.S.C. 4107(d), authorizes the Secretary to award grants to persons engaged
in commercial fisheries, for uninsured losses determined by the Secretary to have been suffered as a direct result
of a fishery resource disaster. Set forth below are the conditions and definitions established by the Secretary to
implement the programs described in part III. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The IFA requires that ``the Secretary shall determine the extent, and the beginning and ending dates of any fishery
resource disaster'' (16 U.S.C. 4107(d)(2)). Although there have been declining trends in landings from the salmon
fisheries in recent years, a sharp decline did not occur until after 1991. This sharp decline coincided with an extreme
El Nino ocean warming event during 1992&hyph;993. The 1994 season is the first season in which all ocean fisheries
for coho were closed; the projected chinook harvest for ocean fisheries indicates a new record low will be achieved,
eclipsing the previous record low in 1992. Therefore, for the purposes of the proposed NEAP program, the beginning
and ending dates of the fishery resource disaster are January 1, 1992, and December 31, 1994, respectively. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The extent of this disaster includes the waters and habitat associated with the salmon fisheries of northern California,
Oregon and Washington. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

